            <div class="paragraph_content">
              <b>Brief History and Outline of present work</b><br/>
              <span>The Broadfield Resource Centre (BRC) idea began with the initiation of local meetings with key agencies and service user organisations in 2011 to identify and prioritise community needs, develop strong working partnerships and good inter agency communication.</span>
            </div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">
              The Broadfields Resource centre is a brainchild of Open Heavens Church which moved to Broad fields in 2008 and has established a strong presence in the neighbourhood maintaining a priority commitment to community support. The Church has become increasingly aware of growing community support needs, hence the idea of starting a separate charitable company the Broad fields Resource Centre to provide a visible community base from which to offer voluntary community services. Information on support needs has come from the Profile of Children and young people in Barnet (Nov 2010); directly from local people already in touch with the Church and Centre; from liaison with a range of local statutory, voluntary and service user organisations. This is also supported by several publicly available stats of Barnet and other neighbouring boroughs. 
            </div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">The original aim of the Resource Centre is to help families and young people improve the quality of their lives through opportunities for family/individual growth and mutual support. The Broadfields Community Resource Centre is well located for the neighbourhood and geographically accessible. It presently provides a small counselling service and children’s nursery and young adults development initiatives in partnership with the church, Open Heavens Christian Centre and Blueskies nursery. </div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">
              Without any external funding support presently, The Centre’s accommodation was significantly improved with a £450,000 project funded from church donations, enabling potential further service development. The BRC services are currently publicised with other organisations e.g. local schools, information leaflets at key venues e.g. libraries; presentations at local events (e.g the Edgware Summer Festival); members of the Church congregation and other local churches. Self-referrals and referrals from other agencies are accepted.
            </div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">
              <b>Operational update:</b><br/>
              <span>The Broad fields Resource Centre has been established and registered as a charity, many committed volunteers have been recruited with strong qualifications and skills for working with families and young people through a vigorous leadership development process in partnership with the Church.</span>
            </div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">A small counselling and youth/young adult development programme have been established; a Day nursery opened within the facility in partnership with Blueskies. Initial procedures and systems have been put in place to support the various programme and projects development e.g. up to date safeguarding and CRB checking processes On-going Plans for continuous improvement of the accommodation and Centre facilities</div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">
              <b>BRC Plans:</b>
              <span>
                <ul>
                  <li>Recruit Project Development Director </li>
                  <li>Recruit a part time Project Development officer. The Project Worker will work with the Committee, partner organisations, service users and current volunteers to move forward the Centres capacity and development opportunities.</li>
                  <li>Beneficiaries of our services include the local community; family, individuals and young people; other organisations. The community will benefit through increased family and individual resilience gained from the support offered by the Centre, helping them face and deal with adverse and stressful life situations. Through families and individuals gaining knowledge and skills to overcome problems, increasing self-confidence, they are more able to form strong relationships, needless support and can contribute positively within family and neighbourhood settings.</li>
                  <li>Families and individuals will gain from the direct service support not only to overcome current problems and improved relationships, but to develop coping strategies and self belief to manage any new problems.</li>
                  <li>Other agencies will benefit by being able to refer people to the Centre for support, complementing their own approach.</li>
                  <li>The Counselling Service and Pilot Courses will particularly focus on working with families and young people facing identifiable emotional, relationship or economic/practical problems in their lives. The emotional problems could include depression, stress or anxiety; relationship problems within the family or community; economic problems caused by unemployment, debt or homelessness</li>
                  <li>Access to the counselling service and pilot courses will be through individual needs assessment and a commitment by the participant to work on their problems.</li>
                  <li>The Youth Project will benefit all young people who join and also their families. The service will be of particular value to young people who lack confidence, or have become isolated, by providing stimulating non-threatening learning and friendship forming opportunities.</li>
                  <li>Access to the Youth project is open to all young people from the neighbourhood between the ages of ………….</li>
                  <li>Volunteers will gain from the project through training and personal development opportunities, gain knowledge and skills and a feeling of achievement from contributing to helping others. People who use the support services will be encouraged to become volunteers as they become more secure and it will also provide a valuable experience in job preparation.</li>
                </ul>
              </span>
            </div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">
              <b>Location of services:</b><br/>
              <span>The counselling and youth service will be ongoing through the year; the 3 pilot courses will commence in January 2019; volunteer recruitment and possible funding applications will be considered later for stability & sustainability.</span>
              <span>
                <ul>
                  <li>To enhance/facilitate the key strategic outcomes for Barnet.</li>
                  <li>A successful London Suburb - Strong safe communities for every one</li>
                  <li>Investing in Children, Young people and their families - healthy and independent living</li>
