            <div class="paragraph_content">Open heavens Church and the Broad fields Resource Centre volunteers have become increasingly aware of the significant needs of families and young people in the area through direct contact with some of the people struggling to cope and reports on need from congregation and visitors to the Church and Centre. It has become evident that the current economic climate is placing pressure on families and young people with unemployment, job insecurity and a range of financial pressures. The stresses are showing themselves in presenting relationship and emotional concerns – feelings of isolation, anxiety states, depression, low self-esteem and a lack of confidence to confront their problems. Feedback surveys from young people indicate a lack of encouraging and engaging opportunities in the area to stimulate interest, gain support and meet other young people.</div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">In recent months the BRC team have developed significant partnerships with organisations such as Christians against Poverty, The Tearfund, Cinnamon network and also received significant advice and support from CommUNITY Barnet and representatives of local statutory service, checking and confirming perceptions of need in the area and lack of service provision; research has been undertaken into national needs trends and responses and the information provided by Barnet Council, particularly the Profile of Children and Young People in Barnet has informed our approach to meeting needs. Meetings have taken place and visits have been made to a range of other local voluntary and statutory agencies to explore needs in the area and opportunities for joint working. </div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">The objective of the Broad fields Resource Centre project is to help improve the well being of residents in the area by strengthening resilience and building up what has been termed “social capital.” Resilience is seen as the capacity to recover from adverse and stressful events and regain good well being and positive social status. Having dealt with the distressing or adverse situation once, knowledge, skills and confidence are built up to help that person, family or community resist down turns on following occasions. The projects will strengthen resilience skills at individual, family and community level by providing participatory activities, learning opportunities with low barriers for receiving help.</div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">Empirical evidence (Putnam 2000) and local feedback demonstrates that strong social capital significantly impacts on crime reduction, educational achievement and even life expectancy. Strong social capital is founded on connections of friendship, neighbourhoods and trust which the Broadfield Resource Centre will aim to build with its partners and people who use the services. It will especially benefit people living isolated lives, perhaps due to their emotional state. Research also high lights that social capital relies on physical reality and those purely virtual links (such as the internet) alone are too “thin” to build up trust and introduce good coping mechanisms. The Centre will provide a visible and secure base from which to provide enabling services and reach out to the community.</div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">National research (Putnam 2000) stresses that improved social capital has a beneficial impact on the quality of life for members of the community not directly involved in such projects. They benefit from the increased security/changed behaviours of those directly engaged and that resilience skills last beyond the time and resources invested in learning and support. In this way, the project will continue to have substantial impact beyond the individual period of direct contact. (Carver 1998; Bayliss 2003)</div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">The funding of a part time Project Development post and two Pilot courses will provide impetus and experience for this new Resource Centre project. The project aims fit well with the criteria identified in the Funding Information P5 6.1 and will focus on individuals and families with identifiable emotional, relationship and practical living needs and on the broad developmental and recreational needs of young people living in the area by: Counselling project – recruit and support an additional 4 volunteer Counsellors to secure and extend the newly created service; in 2012/13 to work with a minimum of 25 people (families, couples, individuals)</div>

            <div class="paragraph_content">Outcomes – identify key problems and triggers; develop coping strategies; change inappropriate/unhelpful attitudes and behaviour; strengthen interpersonal relationship; create greater self confidence and personal security; enable children and young people over come struggles within the family setting; more able to participate positively in other life areas e.g. work, school</div>

